FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, BLUETONGUE - UK (ENGLAND)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
In this update:
[1] FMD Surrey: 7th outbreak confirmed
[2] FMD Hampshire: 1st suspicion refuted; 2nd suspected outbreak
[3] FMD/BT Defra's updated strategy
[4] FMD/BT 2nd Official epidemiological report
******
[1] FMD Surrey: 7th outbreak confirmed
Date: Mon 24 Sep 2007
Source: DEFRA News release, Ref 322/07 [edited]
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2007/070924c.htm>

Positive test results for Foot and Mouth disease (FMD) have now been
confirmed at the site where it was decided that cattle should be
slaughtered on suspicion earlier today [24 Sep 2007]. The site is
within the existing Egham Protection Zone in Surrey, and this becomes
the 7th Infected Premises since 3 Aug 2007.
Minor changes are being made to the Protection Zone (PZ) and
Surveillance Zone (SZ) in the area.
It remains essential for animal keepers to practice the highest
standards of biosecurity, remain vigilant for disease and report any
suspicions immediately. Livestock owners should examine their
livestock twice a day.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall
[According to the BBC citing Defra, this herd was killed at a farm in
Englefield Green near Egham. It is becoming the 5th outbreak since
the start of the 2nd FMD "wave" (which was actually a continuation of
the initial outbreak), within the Egham area. - Mod.AS]
******
[2] FMD Hampshire: 1st suspicion refuted; 2nd suspected outbreak
Date: Mon 24 Sep 2007
Source: BBC News [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7009806.stm>

Another suspected new case of FMD is being investigated at a farm in
Hampshire, the National Farmers' Union has said.
Officials have said a suspected new case of FMD on the Hampshire-West
Sussex border was a false alarm [It will be helpful to note if
bluetongue has been excluded in the said case. - Mod.AS].
The latest suspected case is in the West Tytherly area, near
Stockbridge. [For the official declaration of a temporary control
zone with map, see
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/fmd/pdf/declaration-tcz240907.pdf>.
- Mod.AS]
Farmers have called for aid packages for those worst affected by the
crisis. National Farmers' Union (NFU) president Peter Kendall has
warned that farmers are facing "financial Armageddon" as a result of
the crisis.
Some 1800 animals have so far been slaughtered, but some of the
movement restrictions outside the current surveillance zone have been lifted.
An earlier outbreak in August 2007, which affected 2 premises, was
blamed on the virus escaping from leaking pipes at the nearby
Pirbright laboratory site.
Government chief vet Debby Reynolds said farmers should remain
vigilant for both the bluetongue and the foot-and-mouth virus.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
