[4] FMD/BT 2nd Official epidemiological report
Date: Mon 24 Sep 2007
Source: Feedstuffs [edited]
<http://www.feedstuffs.com/ME2/dirmod.asp?sid=F4D1A9DFCD974EAD8CD5205E15C1CB42&nm=Breaking+News&type=news&mod=News&mid=A3D60400B4204079A76C4B1B129CB433&tier=3&nid=FB33D1DD1CCA4611A856A5C4BAAEDB16>

Today [24 Sep 2007], the United Kingdom's Department For Environment,
Food And Rural Affairs [DEFRA] published the latest FMD epidemiology
report produced by the National Epidemiology Emergency Group. It
concludes that infected premises (IP) 5 provides a link between the
August and September 2007 cases with it probably being infected by
mechanical transmission, either from the Pirbright site or one of the
1st 2 Infected Premises in the Elstead area. It also concludes that
IPs 3 and 4 were probably infected subsequently.
The report also states there have been limited animal movements out
of the Surrey area, in part due to the restrictions in place in
August 2007, which have reduced the risk of wider spread. In
addition, the report concludes that the future course of the outbreak
is dependent on the surveillance for infection and disease by both
animal keepers and Animal Health patrols. Intensive surveillance is
already underway on a precautionary basis in the wider Egham and
Surrey areas. Further surveillance by cattle blood testing will take place.
Based on the epidemiological report and the overall assessment of
risk, 2 FMD risk areas will come into effect from 3.30 pm Tue 25 Sep
2007 [See item 3 "Defra's updated strategy" above].
--
